SIMPLE: aggravation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Aggravation
<hw>Ag`gra*va"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>aggravatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>aggravation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of aggravating, or making worse; -- used of evils, natural
or moral; the act of increasing in severity or heinousness; something
additional to a crime or wrong and enhancing its guilt or injurious
consequences.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exaggerated representation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By a little <qex>aggravation</qex> of the features changed it into
the Saracen's head.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An extrinsic circumstance or accident which
increases the guilt of a crime or the misery of a calamity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Provocation; irritation.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Aggravative</ent>⟦br⟧
